fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-092",
  description: "Parser error span recovery: tighten the failure window so a single-construct error inside a sort body does not subsume the rest of the body in the error span. Symptom observed during WI-085 diagnosis: a malformed effects clause (\"effects (Modify self)\" instead of \"effects Modify[self]\") at byte 316 produced a parse error spanning 316..1947 — almost the entire sort body. Bisection by truncating the file made later innocent constructs (multi-line imports, trailing effects before end) look like they were the trigger, since each truncation either ended on the bad clause (failed) or after it (passed). Fixing the real bug was easy once isolated, but the diagnostic was actively misleading. Improvement: per-clause recovery in the operation/sort body so the error span ends at the next recognizable clause boundary (\"effects\", \"requires\", \"operation\", \"end\"). Should not require grammar changes — tree-sitter has explicit ERROR recovery hooks. Likely a few-hour change to grammar.js plus regenerate.  Driver: improves debuggability for everyone authoring anthill specs; webots-modelling/lf1 was the first project with enough hand-authored binding files to surface this.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-093",
  description: "Time stdlib (anthill.prelude.time): minimal time vocabulary needed for simulation, scheduling, and impurity reasoning. Three pieces. (1) Tick effect — sort Tick with fact Effect[T = Tick]. Operations marked 'effects Tick' depend on or advance simulation/wall-clock time; two calls separated by a Tick are not interchangeable. (2) Clock resource — sort Clock with entity clock, plus operations: now(c: Clock) -> Timestamp effects Tick; advance(c: Clock, by: Duration) -> Unit effects {Modify[c], Tick}. (3) Arithmetic on existing Duration / Timestamp data shapes from primitives.anthill — addition, subtraction, comparison, Numeric and Ordered satisfaction facts as appropriate. Driver: lf1 webots example wants Design B effect modeling — sensor reads stay pure (referentially transparent within a tick, matching webots's contract that sensor values update only via Robot::step), and Robot::step is the only Tick-emitting op. Without a Tick effect we can't express this, so all impurity is currently flattened into Modify. Connected to safety.anthill's inductive_invariant which already reasons in discrete steps; Tick on step makes the proof transition explicit. Out of scope: real-time / wall-clock semantics, time zones, scheduling primitives — those are separate stdlib chunks once concrete consumers appear.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-094",
  description: "World naming predicate for webots (and other simulator) bindings. Tightens the string-typed coupling between controller code and world-file device names by modeling them as anthill facts. Three fact shapes: (1) RobotKind(name, devices: List[NamedDevice]) — devices baked into a robot proto, e.g. Mavic2Pro's gps/gyro/inertial-unit/4-propellers. (2) WorldRobot(world, name, kind, extra_devices: List[NamedDevice]) — robot instance in a specific world, with per-instance additions like a radio Emitter or Receiver. (3) NamedDevice(name, sort) — a (name, anthill-sort) pair. Plus a derived predicate has_device(world, robot, device, sort) :- WorldRobot(...), RobotKind(...), in_devices(...) that binds (world × robot × device-name) to its sort. Codegen check: every Robot.get_X(r, lit_name) call where lit_name is a String literal triggers a query has_device(?world, r.name, lit_name, X); a mismatch produces a typed warning at codegen time. Same name resolving to different sorts on different robots (radio = Emitter on leader, Receiver on followers) is naturally captured per-robot. Driver: lf1 example. First implementation: webots/robot_kinds.anthill listing Mavic2Pro's standard devices; per-world file under examples/webots-modelling/lf1/ listing the lf1 world's robot instances and extras. Codegen-side check is a follow-up under the eventual anthill-cpp-gen WI; the model itself is useful even without the check (tooling, documentation, supervisor-dispatch). Generalizes beyond webots: a Gazebo or hardware target would have its own robot kinds and world-file analogues.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

fact WorkItem(
  id: "WI-095",
  description: "Finish proposal 002 (arrow sorts) implementation. Source grammar/loader/IR for arrow types is already in. Remaining: (a) author Functor/Applicative/Monad typeclass sorts in stdlib using existing arrow syntax; (b) operation-name-as-value (eta-expansion) so 'flatMap(m, pure)' parses with 'pure' as a value; (c) term-headed application '?f(?x)' for arrow-sorted variables, with Miller-pattern unification in the resolver; (d) effect subtyping for arrow types — '(A) -> B <: (A) -> B @ E'; (e) C++ codegen lowering for 'arrow' / 'arrow_effect' functor terms to 'std::function<R(Args...)>'; (f) higher-kinded codegen — when a sort parameter's body declares its own type params, emit 'template<template<typename...> class F>' instead of 'typename F' so Functor/Monad-style sorts compile to C++. The nested-body source form 'sort F { sort T = ? }' already encodes the kind information; codegen just needs to read it. See docs/proposals/002-arrow-sorts.md.",
  acceptance: [ToolPasses("cargo-test")],
  depends_on: [],
  status: Open)

